Whizbang-<br>
<br>
Thanks for that post.  I'll simply reiterate the large amount of common sense and reality in your pointlist contradicts the &quot;INJUSTICE!&quot; cry you spew at every turn where possible.  Your first post on this very thread (not even related to manaburn):<br>
&quot;The MB nerf was always a joke.&quot;<br>
&quot;They just nerfed MB in Kunark (yes, yes, it would have to be flagged unusable in PoP or something too, I agree) to shut up all the whining morons who'd been lied to and told that the reason they didn't have their epics was because ebil wizards were &quot;holding them for ransom.&quot;<br>
<br>
None of this really agrees with your points list, IMO.<br>
<br>
I do have specific disagreements with a couple of your points, but 90% of what you have is what I'd consider mostly correct or at least closer to reality than tromping around town asserting the manaburn nerf was a &quot;joke&quot; (outside of the needed nerf/change for PoP or big raid encounters- specifically against &quot;trivial&quot; kunark content).<br>
<br>
That's truly our only difference of opinion.  I agree the content in question is &quot;trivial&quot; by a standard group- heck, no less trivial than your average pickup vox/naggy style raid where a bunch of random noob 50/51's can form and drop these with little difficulty most of the time.  BUT- I disagree that manaburn didn't make them substantially LESS trivial, as &quot;content&quot; in the form of aggro, summoning, mob retaliation/AE, and some mobs even with cheal... is totally bypassed.  The equivalent triviality could only be arrived by gathering 15-17+ noob wizards and executing a synchronized nuke, which doesn't even figure from the sheer numbers involved and efforts to orchestrate such a synchronized nuke fest.<br>
<br>
I never said mobs were &quot;ganked&quot;- just that there were hit by a group of people less interested in the encounter, and usually without any personal need for the result of the encounter.. and done so by bypassing any content the already trivial encounter had to offer in the first place.  A small, low-tier guild may actually have some members interested in taking down an epic/kunark mob rather than buy the drops from a wizard's alt bazaar mule, or have to &quot;warm up&quot; to a TMB member in hopes of getting a hand-out.  And there is no denying the fact this was the case on Vaz from the entire time TMB was around. (read some of the other posts in this thread and try to deny this, not to mention the influx of scales, RBBs and whatnot that occurred and could be specifically linked to a TMB hit).  I don't care if the intentions of the group were &quot;Robin Hood&quot; of hand-outs to niche-pal rings for free, or the extreme TNZ fallacy of &quot;holding hostage&quot; drops- both scenarios are equally wrong and for the wrong reason, IMO.<br>
<br>
Those were my points.  Plain and simple.  You have the right to disagree with them, or instead can simply do ghetto teenage &quot;gangstah&quot; retorts of juvenile nature concerning levels, titles, raid hit target credentials, and a whole slew of completely incorrect/false labeling.   Your last post at least shows you have some form of civility left at the end of the day, so that says something.<br>
